text: ANTIMICROBIAL AGENTS AND CHEMOTHERAPY, Apr. 1994, p. 637-640 0066-4804/94/$04.00+0 Copyright C 1994, American Society for Microbiology The identification of novel tetracycline analogs able to circumvent the efflux or ribosomal resistance mechanisms could considerably extend the therapeutic utility of this anti- biotic class. Chelocardin and 6-thiatetracycline are analogs discovered in the 1970s; they exhibit the desired profile since they are active against strains resistant to other tetracyclines (Table 2). During the course of studies designed to probe the molecular basis of action of these analogs (8, 9, 11), new insights into the mode of action of these tetracyclines have been obtained. This article reviews these findings and con- cludes that the tetracycline group contains some analogs that do not directly inhibit protein synthesis at the level of the bacterial ribosome. The determinants encoding these resistance mechanisms have been grouped into classes defined by the lack of cross- hybridization under stringent conditions (4, 6). The resistance determinants that mediate active efflux comprise Tet(A) through Tet(F), Tet(K), and Tet(L) (4), and those that confer resistance by ribosomal protection are designated Tet(M) and Tet(O) (4). Many of these determinants are located on plas- mids or within transposable elements and, consequently, have become widely distributed in pathogenic bacteria (4). (This minireview is based on a lecture presented at the 32nd Interscience Conference on Antimicrobial Agents and Chemo- therapy, Anaheim, Calif., 11 to 14 October 1992.) The tetracyclines are a group of broad-spectrum antibiotics which were discovered in 1948 following the isolation of chlortetracycline from Streptomyces aureofaciens (4). Later, other tetracyclines (Table 1) were identified; they were either naturally occurring molecules (tetracycline, demethylchlortet- racycline) or products of semisynthetic approaches (doxycy- cline, minocycline) (4).

The broad spectrum of activity and relative safety of the tetracyclines have led to their extensive use in the therapy of bacterial infections in humans and animals (4). However, one of the most important limitations to the continued widespread use of tetracyclines has been the emergence of bacterial resistance to these antibiotics (4). Two principal mechanisms of resistance occur (4): (i) energy-dependent removal of antibiotic from the cell mediated by membrane-located efflux proteins, and (ii) ribosomal protection whereby tetracyclines are unable to prevent attachment of aminoacyl-tRNA to the ribosomal acceptor site. ham Park, Betchworth, Surrey RH3 7AJ, United Kingdom. Various early studies reported that chelocardin and 6-thia- tetracycline are active against tetracycline-resistant organisms (2, 3, 6, 13, 15). This has been confirmed in a comprehensive study by Oliva and Chopra (8), in which the activities of these tetracycline analogs were examined against Escherichia coli and Staphylococcus aureus strains containing determinants for effiux [Tet(B) or Tet(K)] or ribosomal protection [Tet(M)] (Table 2). E. coli strains bearing Tet(B) or Tet(M) determi- nants display at least a 256-fold increase in resistance to tetracycline. In contrast, susceptibility ratios obtained with chelocardin and 6-thiatetracycline are always <16, and in many cases they are 1 to 2 (Table 2). Thus, Tet(B) and Tet(M) determinants in E. coli offer little or no protection from the analogs chelocardin and 6-thiatetracycline. In S. aureus, nei- ther Tet(K) nor Tet(M) confers substantial levels of resistance to the analogs, since susceptibility ratios of 8 or less are observed, whereas susceptibility ratios of 128 or greater are observed for tetracycline (Table 2). The data presented in Table 2 are based on results obtained with Tet determinants expressed constitutively or induced by the addition of a subinhibitory concentration of tetracycline to the growth me- dium (8).

It is well established that many tetracyclines (e.g., tetracy- cline, chlortetracycline, minocycline, and doxycycline) are bac- teriostatic agents and that this bacteriostatic activity is associ- ated with reversible inhibition of protein synthesis (4, 11). In contrast, it has been known for some time that the tetracycline analogs 6-thiatetracycline and chelocardin are bactericidal rather than bacteriostatic agents (1, 10, 12). These observa- tions imply that chelocardin and 6-thiatetracycline might pos- sess a mode of ribosomal binding that differs from those of tetracyclines with bacteriostatic properties or that the analogs have a separate, distinct mode of action that is unrelated to direct inhibition of protein synthesis at the ribosome. Exposure of ribosomes to tetracyclines that inhibit protein synthesis produced the following two 16S rRNA footprinting patterns: (i) protection of A-892 and stimulation of U-1052/C- 1054, and (ii) failure to protect A-892, but stimulation of U-1052/C-1054. Although chlortetracycline and tetracycline protect A-892, the ribosomal interaction leading to this re- sponse is not directly correlated to inhibition of protein synthesis, since minocycline and doxycycline, which are effec- tive ribosomal inhibitors, do not protect A-892 (Table 3). IDENTIFICATION OF ADDITIONAL ATYPICAL TETRACYCLINES AND DEFINITION OF STRUCTURE- ACTIVITY RELATIONSHIPS WITHIN THE TETRACYCLINE SERIES In addition to chelocardin and 6-thiatetracycline, several other tetracycline analogs that appear to be atypical molecules, i.e., membrane active, bactericidal agents, have been discov- ered (8, 9, 11) (Table 3). This information, together with the results from 16S rRNA footprinting studies, permits conclu- sions on structure-activity relationships for the tetracycline series as a whole to be made (Table 3). Elucidation of the modes of action of chelocardin and 6-thiatetracycline provides a rational molecular explanation for the activities of those compounds against strains expressing Tet(B), Tet(K), or Tet(M) determinants. Thus, tetracycline resistance mechanisms that protect ribosomes [Tet(M)] or that remove antibiotic from the cytoplasm [Tet(B), Tet(K)] are not expected to confer resistance to agents that attack the cyto- plasmic membrane.

CONCLUSIONS The studies reviewed here indicate that tetracycline antibi- otics are divisible into two classes on the basis of their modes of action. Tetracycline, chlortetracycline, minocycline, and doxycycline (typical, or classical, tetracyclines) prevent bacte- rial growth by inhibiting protein synthesis, whereas a second group (atypical tetracyclines) does not directly inhibit bacterial protein synthesis at the level of the ribosome. In contrast to the typical tetracyclines, this second group appears to perturb the organization of the bacterial cytoplasmic membrane, leading to cell death. One of the atypical tetracyclines (6-thiatetracycline) has been administered to human volunteers, but the studies were discontinued following the observance of adverse side effects, in particular, those affecting the central nervous system (12). These adverse effects may well relate to the ability of 6-thiatetracycline to interact with mammalian as well as bac- terial membranes. In addition, the 50% lethal doses of both 6-thiatetracycline and chelocardin obtained in acute toxicity studies in mice are considerably lower than those observed for typical (classical) tetracyclines (7, 12), again possibly reflecting the membrane-disruptive properties of the atypical tetracy- clines compared with those of the typical tetracyclines.

Moreover, in terms of interaction with the whole cell, it is likely that bacterial death occurs by membrane disruption before any potential binding of these analogs to ribosomes within the cell can take place. Finally, there is a set of tetracyclines (chelocardin and 4-epi- anhydrochlortetracycline) that are not ribosomal inhibitors and that do not alter the reactivity of A-892, U-1052, or C-1054 to DMS (Table 3). These features are likely related to substi- tution at C-4 with moieties in the epi (i) configuration (Table 3). Which structural features of tetracycline analogs render them effective membrane perturbants? At physiological pH, many tetracyclines exist as an equilibrium mixture of two free base forms: a low-energy, lipophilic nonionized species and a high-energy, hydrophilic zwitterionic structure (4, 5, 11, 12). The equilibrium between these two forms is influenced by the polarity of the environment, the lipophilic form allowing passage through the cytoplasmic membrane, whereas adoption of the hydrophilic, zwitterionic structure is probably important for ribosomal interaction (5, 12). In contrast to the solvent- dependent equilibrium of the two tetracycline species men- tioned above, chelocardin (and probably the other atypical tetracyclines) apparently exists in the same conformation in both polar and nonpolar solvents, as evidenced by circular dichroism measurements (11). This is probably related to the relative planarity of the BCD rings (i.e., the rings containing carbons 5 through 12) in the atypical tetracyclines, so that a lipophilic form, perhaps related to that of tetracycline, is the preferred species. Therefore, upon interaction with the cell, the atypical tetracyclines are preferentially trapped in the hydrophobic environment of the cytoplasmic membrane, dis-

In view of their modes of action, it is not surprising that the atypical tetracyclines exhibit activity against organisms that are resistant to typical tetracyclines. However, the atypical tetra- cyclines cannot be considered therapeutic candidates because of their potential for causing adverse side effects. It remains to be seen whether tetracycline analogs which retain the ability to inhibit bacterial protein synthesis at the ribosome, while truly circumventing effilux-based or ribosomal resistance mecha- nisms, can be generated.
